The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, June 22, 2004 				 AllBank targets sub 1% NPA by end-fiscal 
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Singh: Fitness fanatic 																								Calcutta, June 21: Allahabad Bank hopes to do business worth Rs 61,000 crore and bring down its bad assets to below 1 per cent this fiscal. 																								In 2003-04, the bank had bagged business worth Rs 47,865 crore while its non-performing assets stood at 2.37 per cent (on March 31, 2004).																								Chairman and managing director . . Singh today unfolded the banks corporate plan for 2004-05 at the second annual meeting held here.																								Singh said the bank would make an operating and net profit in 2004-05, in line with the trends in the past.																								In 2003-04, the banks net profit increased 179.2 per cent to Rs 463.38 crore compared with Rs 165.99 crore in 2002-03. Operating profit grew 69.9 per cent to Rs 876.25 crore against Rs 515.83 crore in the previous year.																								Allahabad Bank has taken up various new initiatives in different operational areas to boost profitability, productivity and efficiency, Singh told shareholders.																								A policy of rationalisation of branches has been adopted at metro centres and new branches have been set up in upcoming growth centres, he added. 																								The bank has merged nine branches and is offering depository participant services at three new centres in Varanasi, Lucknow and Kanpur, apart from Calcutta.																								Allahabad Bank has decided to opt for centralised banking solutions in a big way, the first phase of which will be commissioned soon.																								The bank is setting up a proactive human resources team through a continuous process of skilling and re-skilling of its workforce to meet the challenges of the future. The bank is drawing up a specific HRD plan for this.																								Allahabad Bank will continue to increase its fee-based income in the current fiscal through tie-ups and corporate agency arrangements with leading institutions like LIC, National Insurance, ECGC Limited, UTI Mutual Fund and others.																								The bank has also picked up a 10 per cent stake in Arsec India  the asset reconstruction company promoted by UTI.
